st_crop() without tears

Vanquishing the attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all geometries warnings

Susannah Cowtan

08/02/2022

Cropping a map to a box larger than the data suggest

Im plotting presence records on a coastline map. If I crop the map directly to a box around the data, made using st_bbox(), then for those points which are at the edge, it is a matter of luck whether I can see if they are on the coastline or not. This doesnt work for me; I need to crop the map slightly bigger.

There is also a warning generated when you crop a map geometry which has been generated using rnaturalearth{}: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all geometries. Warnings offend me. I want to get rid of them, and not by putting warning = FALSE in my chunk header. So, here goes.

library(ggplot2)
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(dplyr))
library(rnaturalearth)
library(sf)
## Linking to GEOS 3.8.0, GDAL 3.0.4, PROJ 6.3.1; sf_use_s2() is TRUE

First we make up some minimal, boring data. I cheated and moved them till they were on the coast.

species_df <- tibble(
  Longitude = c(3.8, 3.1, 3.4),
  Latitude = c(43.5, 43, 43.3)
)

I want these to be in simple features format (package sf{}) for compatibility with the map. This has the added advantage that I dont have to get clever with my axis tick labels, that pesky degree symbol is done for me!

# Convert lat/long columns to a column of class geometry
species_sf <- st_as_sf(species_df, 
                       coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"),
                       crs = st_crs(4326))

Three boring points

Now I use the rnaturalearth{} package to get a nice coastline map. This turned out to be the cause of the warning, so I set its relation_to_geometry attribute to be "constant", and this magically gets rid of the problem. There is some explanation of this in the sf vignette but its not exactly easy to follow. When reading it, I figured Id need to set agr to "constant" instead of NA on the data and the crop box too, but that turned out to be unnecessary.

# Coastline geometry from rnaturalearth
coastlines <- ne_coastline(scale = 50, returnclass = "sf") %>%
  # Get rid of the annoying warning from st_crop about 
  # attributes assumed constant
  st_set_agr("constant")

This is the map rnaturalearth::ne_coastline() generates at scale 50

This is the medium resolution map. Its a vector graphic, so you can zoom in by cropping it without it degrading, although if you zoom in too far, it gets a bit pointy. There is a higher resolution version, but you need to install rnaturalearthhires for that, and currently for me, on R 4.1.2, that only works with remotes::install_github().

Now I need to create a box to crop the map to. In my real data, I have thousands of different point locations on some of the maps Im generating, while others have only one. I initially thought Id create a box around the data with st_bbox(), but that doesnt work if you only have a single location. I could put a buffer around each point, and put a box around that. That would be just fine for these three points, but its computationally expensive when there are a lot of points. So what Im actually doing is creating an sf object with only two points, one at the minimum latitude and longitude, and one at the maximum.

# Minmax dataset to crop map
minmax_sf <- tibble(
  Latitude = range(species_df$Latitude),
  Longitude = range(species_df$Longitude)
) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"),
           crs = st_crs(4326))

Now I create my crop box, by putting a buffer around the two points, so instead of them being points they are now circles. The buffer is specified in metres, and Id rather have specified it in degrees, but that doesnt seem to be working optimally.

# Cropped map
buffered_sf <- minmax_sf %>%
    # Apply buffer to minmax points (in metres)
    st_buffer(dist = 50000)

These points are now pretty big circles

Clearly drawing a box around these will make for a better map.

# Cropped map
coast_crop_sf <- buffered_sf %>%
    # Draw box around buffer
    st_bbox(crs = st_crs(species_sf)) %>%
    # Crop to box - look!  No warnings!
    st_crop(coastlines, .)

Now lets project the data onto the map. There is some finicking because I wanted nicely spaced breaks, and scales::breaks_extended() wasnt working for axis ticks generated via geom_sf().

# For adjusting axis limits to get pretty breaks
# Extract the coordinates from the geometry, into columns X and Y
limits_df <- st_coordinates(coast_crop_sf) %>%
  # Didn't want a matrix
  as_tibble() %>%
  # Two rows, first one min, second max
  summarise(across(c(X, Y), range)) %>%
  # Round to nearest 0.5 for pleasing breaks
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ round(2 * .x) * .5))      

ggplot() +
  # Plot the map
  geom_sf(data = coast_crop_sf) +
  # Add the points
  geom_sf(data = species_sf, colour = "#328573", size = 2.5) +
  # Impose the same projection on the whole lot
  coord_sf(crs = st_crs(species_sf)) +
  # Gets me breaks starting at a multiple of 0.5, with separation 0.5
  expand_limits(x = c(limits_df$X - 0.05, limits_df$X + 0.05)) +
  labs(
    x = "Longitude",
    y = "Latitude"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

A map where I can see clearly that all my points are on the coast
